Introduction

We have taken a data set on the student performance on exams regarding math,reading and writing scores. The data set is taken from https://www.kaggle.com/spscientist/students-performance-in-exams We have searched for a data set that is already cleaned. The data set provides information on the student performance at reading writing and math exams together with data about gender, race,parental education,lunch and test preparation . In this report we will explore the data and analyse it.Specifically, we’ll use data visualisation and transformation to explore the choosen data set.

Question: 1.What type of variation occurs within the variables?

2.What type of covariation occurs between the variables?

First, we have to import the data set into the rStudio environment so that we can start explore the data and analyse it.

Moreover, it is shown that male students has better scores in math, while female students have in reading and writing.

There are outliers in all three exams.

In average female students did better than male students, and in average students who completed the test preparation did better than the ones who did not.

Linear regression(Alex Constantinescu):

linearmodel <- lm(Math_Score~avgScore, data= stPerformAvg)
summary(linearmodel)

Interpretation of the linear regression output:

plot(linearmodel)

##Linear regression model: assumptions A linear regression makes certain assumptions about the data, which you must check:

  1. Homoscedasticity of errors: the variance is homogenous

  2. Normality: Errors are normally distributed

  3. Independence of observations: data was collected using valid sampling methods, there are no hidden biases or relationships

  4. The relationship between X and Y is linear (i.e. the line is straight, not curved)

Residual analysis:

#1.Residual vs Fitted: Linearity assumption

This plot shows whether there are non-linear patterns. The red line follows the doted one so it is a perfect scenario. The residuals appear to be equally spread.

#2.Q-Q(quantitive-quantile):Normality assumption This plot shows if the residuals are normally distributed. If they are, they follow the straight line in this plot. We see here that apart from some outliers, the values fall on or around the straight line

#3. Scale-Location: Homoscedasticity assumption:

This plot tests for homoscedasticity, i.e. if the residuals have equal variance along the regression line.

In this plot, we have a lot of cases so the variance is equlaity spreaded among the plot.

#4. Residuals vs Leverage

This plot is used to spot influential cases in the model.
